elites have sought to define European and national identity. This narrative, the author argues, maintains the existence of common historical and intellectual roots, common values, culture and religion. The book explores its powerful legacy in the positive creation of a sense of European unity, the ways in which it has been exploited for ideological purposes, and its impact on non-Christian communities within Europe.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aHistoryxHistorical PeriodsxModern History. 0aTheology and Religious StudiesxModern Church History (19th and 20th Centuries). 0aTheology and Religious StudiesxReligious StudiesxHistory of Religion. 0aTheology and Religious StudiesxReligious StudiesxReligion in Europe. 4aChristentum. 4aEuropa /Geschichte. 4aEuropa /Religion. 4aGeschichtsschreibung. 4aReligionsgeschichte. 7aRELIGION / Religion & Science.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Backlist Complete English Language 2000-2014 PART1z978311023857008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Backlist Theology and Religious Studies 2000-2014 (EN)z978311023854908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Theology and Religious Studies 2000 - 2014z9783110638165oZDB-23-GTR0 cprintz978311018244640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311091461040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110914610423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110914610/original  a978-3-11-023854-9  DGBA Backlist Theology and Religious Studies 2000-2014 (EN)c2000d2014  a978-3-11-023857-0  DGBA Backlist Complete English Language 2000-2014 PART1c2000d2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL 